{ Deep positional manoeuvres to get a rook to the seventh rank. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Ngf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 Bd6 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. O-O Ne7 9. Nb3 Bd6 10. Bg5 O-O 11. Bh4 Bg4 12. Be2 Bh5 13. Re1 Qb6 14. Nfd4 Bg6 15. c3 Rfe8 16. Bf1 Be4 17. Bg3 Bxg3 18. hxg3 a5 19. a4 Nxd4 20. Nxd4 Nc6 21. Bb5 Red8 { Black allows an IQP for rapid development. But Anatoly Karpov manages to restrict black's piece activity. } 22. g4!! { This idea is deep:
White is about to play Re2-Rae1 and f3 to fight along the e-file. However, black may has the idea of Bf5-e6 to block the e-file. This move stops all the chances } 22... Nxd4 (22... Rac8 23. Nf5 Bxf5 24. gxf5 { White has strong attack on the kingside based on f6 } { [%csl Gf6,Gg4][%cal Gf5f6,Gd1g4] }) 23. Qxd4 Qxd4 (23... Qd6 24. Re2 { This is how a plan is based. Try to control the e-file and play f3 only after Re2. } { [%csl Ge1,Gf3][%cal Ga1e1,Gf2f3] }) 24. cxd4 { now Bf5-e6 does not make sense } { [%csl Gf5][%cal Ge4f5,Gf5e6,Gg4f5] } 24... Rac8 { both sides seizes the open file, why is white better?
white's attack is supported by his pawns
b5 outpost bishop is important because black cannot play Re8 to fight against white for the opened e-file } 25. f3 Bg6 26. Re7 b6 (26... Rc2 27. Rae1 { [%csl Ge8,Gb5,Gg6][%cal Ge1e8] }) 27. Rae1! { stops Rc2 by threatening Re8 mate } 27... h6 28. Rb7 { [%csl Ge7][%cal Ge1e7] } 28... Rd6 29. Ree7 { [%csl Gg6,Gf7] } 29... h5 30. gxh5 Bxh5 31. g4! Bg6 32. f4! { The only defender of the f7 pawn is g6 bishop, which will be soon be chased away. } 32... Rc1+ 33. Kf2 Rc2+ 34. Ke3 Be4 35. Rxf7 Rg6 36. g5 Kh7 37. Rfe7 Rxb2 38. Be8 Rb3+ 39. Ke2 Rb2+ 40. Ke1 { [%csl Gd2][%cal Gb2b1,Ge1d2] } 40... Rd6 41. Rxg7+ Kh8 42. Rge7 *


