{ Pawn on d5 and rook on c6 theme. Force opponent's pieces to go to inactive squares. Transfer out attention. }
1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 b6 3. g3 c5 4. Bg2 Bb7 5. O-O g6 6. d4 cxd4 7. Qxd4 Bg7 8. Nc3 d6 9. Rd1 Nbd7 10. Be3 Rc8 11. Rac1 a6 12. b3 O-O 13. Qh4 Rc7 14. Bh3 Qb8 15. Bg5 Bxf3?! (15... Re8) 16. exf3 b5 { It seems good for black but Kramnik is able to establish the similar theme we have seen with a pawn on d5 and rook on c6 } 17. Bxd7! Rxd7 18. Nd5 Nxd5 19. cxd5 { Similar position with rook on c6 and pawn on d5/ } 19... Rc7!? { Aronian offers a pawn sacrifice, which should not be taken because black just gains too much from it. } 20. Rc6! { 1 } 20... Rxc6 { Almost forced. Black cannot leave the e7 pawn hanging forever and f7-f6 is impossible at least now. a6 pawn is also hanging. } 21. dxc6 { [%csl Ga5][%cal Gg5d2,Gd2a5] } 21... Rc8 22. Rc1! { Keeping the c6 passed pawn is important. } 22... e6 23. Bd2!! { Both Ba5 and Qe7 is ready so that the pawn reaches c7. } { [%csl Ga5,Gc7][%cal Gd2a5,Gc6c7,Gh4e7] } 23... Qc7 { [%csl Ga5,Ge7] } 24. a4! { Every plan require some point or other. } { [%csl Ga4][%cal Ga2a4] } 24... d5 (24... bxa4 25. Qxa4 { [%csl Ga5][%cal Gd2a5] }) 25. axb5 { [%csl Gc7] } 25... axb5 26. Qb4 { [%csl Gb5] } 26... Rb8 { [%csl Ga6,Gb4][%cal Gb4a3,Ga3a6,Gd2a5] } 27. Qa3 Bd4 28. Qa6 Be5 (28... h5 { [%cal Gd2a5,Gd4b6] } 29. Ba5 Bb6 30. Bxb6 Rxb6 31. Qxb6 Qxb6 32. c7) 29. f4! { Black's bishop is forced to retreat to d6 } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Ge5d4] } 29... Bd6 30. Ba5 Qc8 31. Qa7! Ra8 32. Qb6 Rb8 33. Qd4! { Switches the attention from one point to another. Now from pushing our c-pawn to gaining the b5 pawn. } 33... b4 34. c7 Ra8 35. Qb6! Bf8 36. Bxb4 Bxb4 37. Qxb4 Qe8 { 1-0 } *


