{ Brief discussion of Over-protection.
centralization. }
1. e4 { Over-protection should only be part of the logical plan, not for the sake of it. } 1... c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. Be2 cxd4 7. cxd4 e6 8. O-O Be7 9. Nc3 Qd6 10. Be3 { Over-protecting the pawn on d4. However, over-protection can never be used a s a substitute for a well thought out plan. For example, if white wants to over-protect here, he can play Qd2 and Rd1, but the rook is better on c1.
Also, instead of Be3, a better choice is to activate our bishop with } (10. Nb5! { The pieces are more logically developed in this way. } 10... Qd8 11. Bf4 Nd5 12. Bg3 a6 13. Nc3 O-O 14. Rc1 Nf6 15. h3 b6 16. a3 Bb7 17. Bd3 Rc8 18. Bb1 b5 19. Qd3 { Rook on c1, queen on d3, bishop on g3 is much better than d1, d2 and e3 repectively. }) *


