1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. exd5 exd5 5. Bd3 Ne7 6. Ne2 O-O 7. O-O Bg4 8. f3 Bh5 9. Nf4 Bg6 10. Nce2 Bd6 11. Qe1 c5! 12. dxc5 Bxc5+ 13. Kh1 Nbc6 14. Bd2 Re8 15. Nxg6 hxg6 16. f4 Nf5 17. c3 d4! { [%csl Ge3][%cal Gf5e3] } 18. c4 { Obviusly black cannot take on d4, but this means for black a pass on on d3 and an outpost on e3. } 18... Qb6 { A mighty over-protection, but the queen on b6 is not only defending the pawn on 4, but having a clear strategic idea in mind. } 19. Rf3 Bb4! { By getting rid of the dark-square bishop, black's f5 knight can land on the e3 outpost } 20. a3 Bxd2 21. Qxd2 a5! { Restraint: everything after b2-b4 and c5 is prevented after this move. } (21... Ne3 { [%csl Gc5][%cal Gb2b4,Gc4c5,Gd4c5] }) 22. Ng1 Re3! { As we discussed at the beginning of the chapter.
Now black tries to over-protect e3 } 23. Qf2 Rae8 { [%csl Ge3] } 24. Rd1 { [%csl Gb3,Gb4][%cal Gb6b3,Gb2b4,Gb3f3,Gb3c2,Gb3a2] } 24... Qb3! 25. Rd2 Nd6 26. c5 Nc4 { Try to force the trade of white's active light-square bishop. The other knight on c6 can go to f5 anyway. } 27. Bxc4 Qxc4 { [%csl Gc6,Gg1] } 28. Rc2 Qd5 29. Rc1 Qe4 { The pressure on the e-file even increases more. The d-pawn can be pushed forward. } { [%csl Ge1][%cal Ge8e1] } 30. f5 Rxf3 31. Nxf3 Qxf5 { [%csl Gd3][%cal Gd4d3] } 32. b4 axb4 33. axb4 Nxb4 34. Qxd4 { [%csl Gd3] } 34... Nd3 35. Rc2 Rc8 36. Rc3 Nxc5 37. h4 b6 38. Ng5 Rf8 39. Rf3 Qd7 40. Qc4 Ne6 41. Rd3 Qc8 42. Qb5 Qc1+ 43. Kh2 Qf4+ 44. g3 Qf2+ 45. Kh1 Qf1+ 46. Kh2 Nc5 { 0-1 } *


