{ The main theme is c4-c5 and gain full control of d-file. By gaining full control of d-file, and lots of ideas like Rh3-f3, white limits black's piece activity. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 5. Ng3 Bg6 6. h4 h6 7. Nf3 Nd7 8. h5 Bh7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Ngf6 11. Bf4 e6 12. O-O-O Be7 13. Ne4 Nxe4 14. Qxe4 Nf6 { [%csl Gh5,Gg5] } 15. Qd3! (15. Qe1 Qd5 16. Kb1 Nxh5 17. Bc1 Nf6 18. Ne5 Qxg2 19. Rg1 Qe4) (15. Qe2 Qd5 16. Kb1 Nxh5 17. Bc1 Nf6 18. Ne5 Qxg2 19. Rhg1 Qe4) 15... Qd5 16. c4 Qe4 17. Qxe4 Nxe4 18. Be3 Nd6 (18... b5) 19. b3 Bf6 20. g4 b5 21. Nd2 Kd7 (21... O-O-O { [%cal Gd8d7,Gh8d8] }) 22. Kc2 Bd8 23. Nf3 Bf6 (23... bxc4 24. Ne5+) 24. Ne5+ Kc7 25. c5! Bxe5 26. dxe5 Nc8 27. Rh3! { The idea is to tie down opponent's rook by attacking the problem on f7 } 27... Ne7 28. Rf3 { Use your rooks to harass the opponent to harass the opponent and make him defend his pawns with big pieces } 28... Rhf8 29. Rd6 a5 (29... Nd5 30. Bd2 { Gaining a tempo by attacking opponent's pieces and force opponent to react } { [%cal Gd2a5] } 30... a5 31. g5! hxg5 32. Bxg5 a4 33. h6 { The rook finds alternative ways to break black's camp } { [%csl Gh6,Gh7] }) 30. g5! hxg5 31. Bxg5 Nf5 { The g5 bishop is controlling the d8-square } 32. Rd1 Kc8 (32... f6 33. Bf4) (32... a4 33. b4 { No counter-play for the opponent }) (32... Rh8 33. Rfd3 Ra7 34. Bd8+) 33. Rfd3 Ra7 34. Rd8+ Rxd8 35. Rxd8+ Kb7 36. Kc3 Ka6 37. Kd3 Rc7 38. Ke4 Kb7 39. Rd1 { Black's position seems solid. So it allows white to indulge himself with one or two superfluous moves before plunging in dagger } 39... Kc8 40. Rd8+ Kb7 41. Kf4 Rc8 42. Rd7+ Rc7 43. Rd3 Kb8 44. Rd8+ Kb7 45. Bf6!! g6 (45... gxf6 46. exf6 { no way to stop Kg5 and h5-h6 }) (45... Rc8 46. Rxc8 Kxc8 47. Bxg7! Nxg7 48. h6) 46. hxg6 fxg6 47. Kg5 { 1-0 } *


