{ Some convert of advantages. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3 a6 6. Bb3 O-O 7. O-O d5 8. exd5 Nxd5 9. h3 Nb6 10. Re1 h6 11. Nbd2 (11. Nxe5 Bxf2+ 12. Kxf2 Nxe5 13. d4) 11... Qxd3 12. Nxe5 Qg3 13. Qf3 Qxf3 14. Ndxf3 Ne7 15. Nd3 Bd6 16. Bf4 { [%csl Gf4][%cal Gd6f4,Gd3f4] } 16... Ng6 (16... Bxf4 17. Nxf4 Nc6 18. Ne5! { And black cannot stop white's rook to invade on e7 }) 17. Bxd6 cxd6 { This is how an advantage on the e-file is transformed to a structural advantage. } 18. Re4! { Attack d6 without moving the strong d3 knight. } 18... a5 19. Rd4 Rd8 (19... a4 20. Bc2 Bf5 21. Rxd6 Nc4 22. Rd5 Be4 23. Rd4 { [%cal Ge4f3] } 23... Bxd3 24. Rxd3) 20. Rd1 d5 { [%csl Gd3,Gd4,Gb5] } (20... Be6 21. Nc5) 21. Nc5 Ne7 22. a4! { stopping a5-a4 before retreating the bishop. } 22... Re8 23. R4d2! { Nf3-d4-b5 is coming. } 23... Nd7 24. Nxd7 Bxd7 25. c4! dxc4 26. Rxd7 cxb3 27. Rxb7 { Now the structural advantage has been converted to the piece activity advantage.
Any judgement on structure should be combined with the piece activity or passivity. Those are not exclusive. } 27... Rab8 28. Rdd7 { Rxe7 tactical threat. Black prefers to give up the pawn on f7 instead of the pawn on b3 } { [%csl Gf8][%cal Gg8f8] } 28... Nc6 29. Rxf7 Rxb7 30. Rxb7 Re4 31. Rxb3 Rxa4 { piece activity has been converted into material advantage. } 32. Rb6 Rc4 33. g3! { White needs to keep the knights on the board to continue his attacking theme } 33... a4 34. h4 Nd4 35. Ne5! Rc5 36. Rb8+ Kh7 37. Nd7 Rb5 38. Ra8! { Keeping up pressure to black's king } 38... Ne2+ 39. Kg2 Rxb2 40. h5! { Now the material advantage is converted back to piece activity, that is the pressure against black's king. } 40... Nc3 41. Ne5 Rb5 42. f4 Ne4 { [%csl Gf6][%cal Ge4f6] } 43. g4 Nf6 44. Ng6 Ng8 { Now black's knight is restricted } 45. Nf8+ Kh8 46. Ng6+ Kh7 47. Kf3 Rb3+ 48. Ke4 a3 49. Nf8+ Kh8 50. Ng6+ Kh7 51. g5 hxg5 52. fxg5 Rb4+ 53. Kf5 Rb5+ 54. Kg4 Rb4+ 55. Kf5 Rb5+ 56. Kg4 Rb4+ 57. Nf4 a2 (57... Rb3 58. g6+ Kh8 59. Ne6 { [%cal Ge6g5,Gg5f7] } 59... a2 60. Ng5 { [%csl Gb7] } 60... Rb7 61. Nf7+ Rxf7 62. gxf7) 58. Rxa2 Ne7 59. Ra8 Ng8 60. Ra7 (60. g6+ Kh8 61. Kg3 Rxf4!) 60... Kh8 61. Ra8 Kh7 62. Rf8 Kh8 63. Kf3 { White's plan is now putting the king on e4 and shelter it with Nd5 } 63... Rb3+ 64. Ke4 Rb4+ 65. Ke5 Rb5+ 66. Nd5 Ra5 67. Rd8 Kh7 68. g6+ Kh8 69. h6! { The decisive move } 69... Ra7 (69... gxh6 70. Rd7! { [%csl Gh7][%cal Gd7h7] }) 70. Ne3! (70. h7? Re7+ 71. Kd6 Re6+ $10 { etc }) 70... gxh6 71. Nf5! { Nf5, Kh5, Rf8, Black's rook is tied to defend on 7th rank and then Rf7 is the target winning theme for white. } { [%csl Gh5] } 71... Ra5+ (71... Rb7 72. Kf4! (72. Nxh6? Kg7 73. Nxg8 Kxg6 $10)) (71... Ra1) 72. Kf4 Ra4+ 73. Kf3 Ra3+ 74. Kg4 Ra4+ 75. Kh5 Ra7 (75... Ra5 76. g7+ (76. Rf8 Rb5 77. Rf7 { [%cal Gf7h7] } 77... Rb6 (77... Ne7 78. Rxe7 Rxf5+ 79. Kxh6 { [%cal Gf5f8] } 79... Rf6) 78. Rh7#)) 76. Rf8 Rb7 77. Kh4 { Playing it safe } (77. Rf7 { Already wins }) 77... Rb4+ 78. Kh5 Rb6 79. Ne7 Kg7 80. Rf7+ Kh8 *


