{ ALL those prophylactic moves are just so deep and strong, }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Be2 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. f4 Nc6 9. Be3 Bd7 (9... Nxd4 10. Qxd4 Bd7 { [%cal Gd7c6] } 11. e5) 10. Nb3! { Stops Nxd4 Bxd4 Bc6 to force the d7 bishop to remain passive on d7 } 10... a5?! (10... a6) (10... Qc7) 11. a4 { Another important restraining move. Holds the b5 square without occupying it. Also stops a5-a4-a3 } 11... Nb4 12. Bf3 { Prophylaxis against Bc6 } 12... Bc6 { It seems that black is planning d5 e5 Ne4 } 13. Nd4! g6 { Now black decided to prepare e6-e5 } (13... e5 14. Nf5) 14. Rf2 { Saw e6-e5 is about to be played and the f-file is about to be opened } 14... e5 15. Nxc6 bxc6 16. fxe5 dxe5 17. Qf1! Qc8 18. h3! { Ng4 is not yet a threat, but Karpov prevents it from the long term. Also wait and gives black chances to make mistakes } 18... Nd7 { White does not want to allow Bc5 } { [%csl Gc5][%cal Ge7c5] } 19. Bg4! h5 20. Bxd7 Qxd7 21. Qc4! { Preserving the dark-square bishop deprive all black's counter-play } 21... Bh4 22. Rd2 Qe7 23. Rf1! { Simple moves are enough for a win } (23. Bc5 Qg5 24. Rd7 Nxc2 25. Bxf8 Rxf8) 23... Rfd8 (23... Rad8! { [%csl Gc5,Gb7] }) 24. Nb1! { Clears place for c2-c3, and improving the unprotential knight with Nd2-f3 } 24... Qb7 25. Kh2! { White's king secures himself from kinds of checks and ready for g2-g3 } 25... Kg7 26. c3 Na6 27. Re2! { Keep b defended and ready for Nd2-f3 } 27... Rf8 28. Nd2 Bd8 29. Nf3 f6 30. Rd2! { Perfect piece coordination! Now all pieces are in perfect spots! Bad bishop is traded, all pieces are active. } 30... Be7 31. Qe6! { Now it is time for making use of holes in black's position } 31... Rad8 32. Rxd8 Bxd8 33. Rd1 Nb8 34. Bc5 Rh8 35. Rxd8! { 1-0 } *


