1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 c6 4. Nc3 Bf5 5. Qb3 Qb6 6. Qxb6 axb6 7. cxd5 Nxd5! 8. Nxd5 cxd5 9. e3 Nc6 10. Bd2 Bd7! { [%csl Ge7][%cal Gc6a5,Gb6b5,Ga5c4] } 11. Be2 e6 12. O-O Bd6 13. Rfc1 Ke7 14. Bc3 Rhc8 15. a3 Na5 16. Nd2 f5 17. g3 b5 18. f3 Nc4 { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gd2c4,Gb5c4,Ge3e4] } 19. Bxc4 bxc4 20. e4 Kf7 21. e5?? (21. exd5 exd5 22. f4) 21... Be7 22. f4 b5 { [%csl Gb4][%cal Gg7g5,Gb5b4] } 23. Kf2 Ra4 24. Ke3 Rca8 25. Rab1 h6 26. Nf3 g5 27. Ne1 { The threat is stronger than the execution.
Just as the previous example, like the principle of two weaknesses, act on one side but seriously targeting another.
Now b5-b4 is unpreferrable for activating the bad bishop on c3
The change of direction } 27... Rg8! 28. Kf3 gxf4 29. gxf4 Raa8! 30. Ng2 Rg4 31. Rg1 Rag8 32. Be1 b4!! { Only now we are planning to put the d7 bishop in the way in.
Because this is stronger NOW } 33. axb4 Ba4 34. Ra1? Bc2 35. Bg3 Be4+ 36. Kf2 h5! 37. Ra7 Bxg2 38. Rxg2 h4 39. Bxh4 Rxg2+ 40. Kf3 Rxh2 41. Bxe7 Rh3+ 42. Kf2 Rb3 43. Bg5+ Kg6 44. Re7 Rxb2+ 45. Ke3 Ra8 46. Rxe6+ Kh7 { 1-0
How you change direction (PREPARE AT ONE SIDE THAT YOU ARE POSSIBLE TO OPEN UP AND OPEN UP ANOTHER SIDE) and fight on the two front. Suddenly switch direction and suddenly switch again. Open up the position only when you are ready to or only when you are sure it is the strongest moment. } *


