[UTCTime "19:20:41"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. c3 Qb6 6. Qb3 d5 7. Nbd2 Bd7 8. Be2 cxd4 9. exd4 Bd6 10. O-O h6 11. Bh4 Nh5 12. Qxb6 axb6 13. Rfe1 g5 14. Bg3 Nxg3 15. hxg3 f6 16. g4 Kf7 17. Nh2 { Carry out a fimilar knight manoeuvre to strengthen his pawns and fix a space advantage on the queenside. } 17... Na5! 18. Nhf1 b5 19. a3 Nc4 20. Nxc4 bxc4 21. Ne3 { tie white pieces down to defend the queenside and then open up the fresh line of attack on the kingside. White pieces won't be able to adjust needs
Try to analyze weaknesses } 21... Ra6 22. g3 Rb6 23. Ra2 Ra8 24. Bf3 Ra5 25. Kg2 Rab5 26. Re2 { [%csl Ge2,Ga2] } 26... Be8 27. Rd2 Kg7 28. Bd1 Bg6 { Now while all the white's pieces cannot take any actions, black better his other pieces step-by-step } 29. Ba4 Ra5 30. Bc2 Bxc2 31. Rxc2 Kg6 32. Re2 Rab5 33. Nd1 Bf8! { Bishop retreats in order to allow rook swings to the kingside } 34. Ra1 h5! { Now since all white' pieces are tied up defending, kingside can be opened up } 35. f3 hxg4 36. fxg4 f5! { Now we can understand how Bf8 is allowing the rooks to the kingside } 37. gxf5+ exf5 38. Rc1 Rf6 39. Rcc2 Bd6 40. Re8 Kf7 41. Re1 f4 42. g4 f3+! 43. Kf2 Rh6! { Now white will be forced into an unpleasant pin } 44. Kxf3 Rh3+ 45. Ke2 Rh2+ 46. Nf2 Bg3 47. Rf1? (47. Kf1 Rxf2+ 48. Rxf2+ Bxf2 49. Kxf2 Rxb2+ 50. Re2) 47... Rb6! { The entrance of the other black's rook is decisive } { [%csl Gf6][%cal Gb6f6] } 48. Kf3 Bh4 49. Re2 Rf6+ 50. Ke3 b5 51. Rd2 Ke7 { [%csl Gf2][%cal Ge7d7,Gd7c7,Gc7b6,Gb6a5,Ga5a4,Ga4b3,Gb3b2,Gb2c3,Gb2a3] } 52. b4 cxb3 53. Nd3 Rxd2 54. Kxd2 { 0-1
Analyze weaknesses or lines that can be opened up. Then,
By attacking one side (weaknesses) or threating to open up one line, tie up opponent's pieces or disorder opponent's pieces and open up another line on the other side. } *


