{ The idea of putting the pawn alongside the apex of pawn chain }
1. Nf3 Nf6 2. d4 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 Be7 5. e3 O-O 6. a3 a6 { [%cal Ga7a6] } 7. c5 { In nimzo's word, not giving up the center, but to change the focus of the attack from d5 to c6 } { [%csl Gb5,Gc5] } 7... c6 8. b4 Nbd7 { [%csl Gb4,Gb5,Ga4] } 9. Bb2 Qc7 10. Qc2 e5 { [%csl Gc5,Gb5] } 11. O-O-O (11. dxe5! { Stick on Nimzo's theory is logical here }) 11... e4 { How to deal with this knight? } { [%csl Gf7,Ge4,Gf4][%cal Gf3h4,Gh4g2,Gf3d2,Gd2b3] } 12. Nh4 { [%csl Gf5][%cal Gh4f5] } (12. Nd2 Ng4 13. Nb3) 12... Nb8! 13. g3 { [%csl Gf4,Gf7,Gf5] } 13... Ne8?! (13... a5!) 14. Ng2 f5 15. h4 { Put the pawn alongside the most advantaged pawn. For black, he wants to put the pawn on f4. For white it is b5 } { [%csl Gf4][%cal Gh4g5,Gg2f4] } 15... Bd8 16. a4 b6 17. b5 Nf6 18. Nf4 axb5 19. axb5 Qf7 20. Be2 Bc7 21. cxb6 Bxf4 22. gxf4 Bd7 23. Kd2 cxb5 24. Ra1 { [%csl Gb6,Ga7] } *


