{ Launching the strategic plan. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nd4 4. Nxd4 exd4 5. O-O g6 6. d3 Bg7 7. Nd2 Ne7 8. f4 c6 9. Bc4 d5 10. Bb3 O-O 11. Nf3 c5 12. e5 b5 13. c3 c4 14. Bc2 dxc3 15. bxc3 Qa5 16. Bd2 Bg4 { [%csl Ge5,Gf4,Gf5] } 17. d4! { Now after solidify the pawn on e5, white is trying to put the other pawn on f5, right besides the e5 pawn. However, like all great strategists, Capa is trying to prevents opponent's pawn before launching the own idea. } 17... Qb6 { [%csl Gc3,Gb4,Gg4,Gf3] } 18. Rb1! { b4 cb and Bxf3 is prevented } 18... a6 { playing passively on the queenside means his queenside majority has no value. } (18... a5 19. h3 Bxf3 20. Rxf3 b4 21. Kh1 Rab8 22. cxb4 Qxd4 23. b5 { [%cal Gb5b6] }) 19. h3 Bf5 { 2 } 20. g4 { Carrying out a strategic plan that suits the requirement of the position } 20... Bxc2 21. Qxc2 f5 { Now white haas a clear idea: Kh2, doubling up rooks along the g-file, play Nh4 or Bc1-a1-e7 to force the open of g-file, where white rooks have crushing power. Also if black plays fxg4, then the idea of f4-f5 will reborn. } { [%csl Gf5,Gh3,Gg4,Gf4] } 22. Kh2 Nc6 23. Rg1 Nd8 24. gxf5 Rxf5 25. Nh4 Rh5 26. Nxg6 hxg6 27. Rxg6 Qb8 28. Rxg7+ Kxg7 29. Rg1+ Kf8 30. Qg6 Rxh3+ 31. Kxh3 *


