{ Preperations before pawn breaks
Pawn push to block the other side before attacking kingside. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. f3 O-O 6. Be3 e5 7. Nge2 a6 8. Qd2 Bd7 9. d5 Ne8 10. g4 h6 11. h4 Kh7 12. Ng3 c5 { [%csl Gg5,Gh7][%cal Gh4h5] } 13. Bd3 Qa5 { [%csl Ga5] } 14. Qe2 Rh8 15. a3 Qd8 { [%csl Gb7,Gb5,Ge1] } 16. b4 b6 17. Qb2 Bc8 18. Ke2 Nd7 { 3 points why playing pawn breaks on queenside when ur intention is on kingside:
1. Attract black’s pieces to the queenside.
2. Gain more space.
3. Block the queenside so that black does not have counter-attack on queenside. } { [%csl Gb3][%cal Ge2d2,Gd2c2,Gc2b3] } 19. Rag1 Rb8 20. b5 { block queenside } 20... a5 (20... axb5 21. cxb5 (21. Nxb5 Ba6) 21... c4 22. Bxc4 Nc5) 21. Kd1 Kg8 22. Qd2 Nf8 23. Kc2 f6 24. g5 fxg5 25. hxg5 h5 { [%csl Gg6][%cal Gf8g6] } 26. Nf5!! { Other ways to put the pawns on the same line. Also the idea is he wants to play f3-f4 without allowing black to play Nf8-d7-e5 } (26. f4 exf4 { [%csl Gd6] } 27. Bxf4 { [%csl Ge5] } 27... Nd7 { [%csl Gd7,Ge5][%cal Gd7e5] }) 26... Kf7 (26... gxf5 27. exf5 Rh7 28. f6 Bh8) 27. Nh4 Qe7 28. Qh2 Nc7 29. Rf1 Ke8 30. f4! { [%csl Gf5,Gf8,Gd7,Ge5,Gg6][%cal Gf4f5] } 30... exf4 31. Bxf4 { Black cannot play Nf8-d7-e5 } { [%csl Gg6][%cal Gh4g6,Gf8d7] } 31... Kd7 32. Bxd6! *


