{ good bishop against bad bishop
spacial advantage in endgame
Active knight and rook position allows king to march forward
f4-f5 breakthrough }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h6 5. g4 { [%csl Gf5][%cal Gf2f4,Gf4f5] } 5... Bd7 (5... Bh7 6. e6 fxe6 7. Bd3) 6. Nd2 c5 7. dxc5 e6 (7... Nc6 8. f4 e6 9. Nb3 Bxc5 10. Nxc5 Qa5+ 11. c3 Qxc5 { [%csl Gd4,Ge3] } 12. Rh3 { [%cal Gc1e3] } 12... h5 { [%csl Ge3][%cal Gd5d4] } 13. Be3 (13. gxh5 Nh6 14. Be3 Qa5 15. Nf3 Nf5 16. Bf2 f6) 13... d4 14. cxd4 Qa5+ 15. Bd2 Qd5) 8. Nb3 Bxc5 9. Nxc5 Qa5+ 10. c3 Qxc5 11. Nf3 Ne7 { [%csl Ge3] } 12. Bd3 Nbc6 13. Be3 Qa5 14. Qd2 Ng6 (14... d4 15. cxd4 Nb4 { [%csl Gc6][%cal Gb4d5,Gd6c6] }) 15. Bd4 Nxd4 16. cxd4 Qxd2+? 17. Kxd2 { 1) White retains the light square bishop
2) White controls the c-file first
3) White's kingside pawns has mobilbility } 17... Nf4 18. Rac1 h5 (18... Nxd3 19. Kxd3 { Good knight against bad bishop }) 19. Rhg1! { No need to play g4-g5 in this case } 19... Bc6 20. gxh5 Nxh5 21. b4! { Both rooks are active on both sides of the board } 21... a6 22. a4 Kd8 { [%csl Gc7] } (22... Bxa4 23. Rc7 Bc6 24. Ng5! Rf8 25. Nxf7 Rxf7 26. Bg6) 23. Ng5 Be8 24. b5 Nf4 25. b6 { Like the very first chapter } 25... Nxd3 26. Kxd3 Rc8 27. Rxc8+ Kxc8 28. Rc1+ Bc6 { [%csl Gh4] } 29. Nxf7 Rxh4 30. Nd6+ Kd8 31. Rg1 Rh3+ 32. Ke2 Ra3 33. Rxg7 Rxa4 34. f4 { Ready for f5 } { [%csl Gf5][%cal Gf4f5] } 34... Ra2+ 35. Kf3 { The king supports the future advance of f4-f5 } { [%cal Gf3g4,Gf4f5] } 35... Ra3+ 36. Kg4 Rd3 37. f5 Rxd4+ 38. Kg5 exf5 39. Kf6 Rg4 40. Rc7 Rh4 41. Nf7+ *


