1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 Be7 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 c6 7. Qc2 Na6 8. a3 O-O 9. e3 Nc7 10. Bd3 Ne6 11. Be5 g6 12. O-O Ng7 13. b4! a6 { Try not to left with a weak a-pawn } 14. Bxf6! { Speeds up the queenside speed. So black can no longer play Bxb4 } 14... Bxf6 15. a4 Bf5 16. Bxf5 Nxf5 17. b5 axb5 (17... cxb5 18. axb5 a5 19. Qb3 { [%csl Gd5] }) 18. axb5 Qd6 { [%csl Gd6] } 19. bxc6 bxc6 20. Na4! { Stop c5 and thus preventing the activication on f6 bishop } 20... Rfb8 21. Nc5 Qe7 22. Nd3 { [%csl Gd3] } 22... Qb7 23. Nfe5 Bxe5 24. Nxe5 Rxa1 25. Rxa1 Ne7 { One weakness is not enough to win the game. So white tries to exploit another } 26. g3! Qb2 27. Qd1 { Fore sure, because white wants to attack the kingside } 27... h5 28. Rc1 Rb6 29. h3! { g3-g4 in mind } { [%csl Gg4][%cal Gg3g4] } 29... Kg7 30. Kg2 Qa3 31. Ra1 Qb2 32. g4 hxg4 33. hxg4 Rb7? 34. Rc1 Qb5 35. Qf3! { Skillfully switch the play between two weaknesses on c6 and kingside f7 } 35... f6 36. g5 Nf5 (36... fxe5 37. Qf6+ Kg8 38. Rh1) 37. gxf6+ Kxf6 38. Rxc6+ Ke7 39. Qf4 { 1-0 } *


