1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 d5 3. d4 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 Nbd7 7. Nf3 c6 8. Bd3 O-O 9. Qc2 Re8 10. O-O Nf8 11. h3 Be6 12. Rfc1 N6d7 13. Bf4 Nb6 14. Rab1 Bd6 15. Ne2 Ng6 16. Bxd6 Qxd6 17. a4! { Prevents Nc4. Also being ready for Qc5-a3 } { [%csl Ga3,Gc5][%cal Gc2c5,Gc5a3] } 17... Rac8 (17... a5 18. b3 { Induce a problem on a5 } { [%csl Ga5,Gc4,Gc2,Gd2][%cal Gc2d2,Gc1c5,Gc5a5,Gb6c4,Gb7b6] }) 18. Qc5! { [%csl Gc5,Gb5][%cal Gd6c5,Gc1c5,Gb2b4,Gb4b5] } 18... Qb8 (18... Qxc5 19. dxc5 Nd7 20. b4 { Changes white's pawn structure. Keeps white's chances on queenside like b4-b5 etc. In exchange of c1 rook cannot target on c6, d4 is available for the knight }) 19. Qa3 { No need to be rush to play a5-a6 etc. White can try to double the rooks first to pressure the b7-c6 structure } { [%csl Gb4,Gc5][%cal Gb2b4,Gc1c5] } 19... a6 20. Rc3 Qc7 21. Rbc1 Ra8 22. Nd2 { Control the c4 point first. Now white can play b2-b4 and followed by b5 without the refusal of Nc4 } { [%csl Gb4,Gb3,Gc4,Gb6][%cal Gb2b4,Gd2b3,Gd2c4] } 22... a5 { [%csl Gb7,Ga4,Gb6][%cal Gb2b4,Gc3b3,Ga5b4,Gb1b6] } 23. Rb1 { b2-b4, Nb3-c5, a5-a6 breaking up the queenside } { [%cal Gb2b4] } 23... Nc8 24. b4 axb4 25. Qxb4 { [%csl Gc5,Gb3,Gb7,Ga4][%cal Gd2b3,Gb3c5] } 25... Nd6 26. Nb3! Bc8 27. a5 Ne7 28. Ng3! { Before taking actions, prevent black's all kinds of freeing ideas such as Bf5 } { [%csl Gf5][%cal Gc8f5] } 28... g6 { [%csl Gc5,Ga5] } 29. Rcc1 { [%csl Gf5][%cal Ge6f5] } (29. Ra1!) 29... h5 { This is bad because of creating another weakness. If there is only one weakness on the queenside, it might be hard to exploit that. } { [%csl Gh5,Gg3,Gg4,Gb7,Gc6,Gd5][%cal Gc8b7] } (29... Nef5 30. Nxf5 Bxf5 31. Bxf5 { Be2 cannot be played here because of the b1 rook } 31... Nxf5 32. Nc5 Reb8 $14 { White only has a slight advantage because it might be hard to win with only one weakness on queenside. } { [%csl Gb8,Gh6] }) 30. Ra1! { [%csl Gb1,Gd3,Gc5][%cal Gc8f5,Gf5b1,Gb3c5] } 30... h4 (30... Nef5 31. Nxf5 Bxf5 32. Be2) 31. Nf1 Bf5 32. Be2! { Black wastes a move rather than immediate Nef5 so that white's rook has time to escape the pin . } { [%csl Gh4] } 32... Ne4 33. Nc5 Nxc5 34. Qxc5 Be6 35. Nd2 Nf5 36. Nf3 { Still not rushing to play a5-a6 until all the pieces are ready } { [%csl Gc6][%cal Gf3e5,Ge5c6,Ga5a6] } 36... Qd8 37. a6! { Eventually! } { [%csl Gc6] } 37... bxa6 38. Rxa6 Rxa6 39. Bxa6 Qa8 (39... Bd7 40. Bd3 Ng7 { [%csl Gh4] } 41. Ne5 Re6 42. Qa7 Be8 43. Rb1 { And white is dominating } { [%csl Gb8][%cal Gb1b8] }) 40. Qxc6 Qxc6 41. Rxc6 Ra8 42. Bd3 { 1-0 h4 pawn also loses } { [%csl Gh4][%cal Gd3f5,Gf3h4] } *


