{ Excellent defend by Capablanca to neutralize white’s space advantage. Trade pieces and use small combinations. Also note the importance of f7-f5 } { [%csl Gb5] }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6 5. c4 Bd7 6. Nc3 g6 7. d4 exd4 8. Nxd4 Bg7 9. Be3 Nge7 10. O-O O-O 11. h3 Nxd4! { Trade pieces in cramped position } 12. Bxd7 Ne2+! { Logical in-between move. White will either play Qxe2, forgetting about the plan of Bd4, or place the knight on a bad square. } 13. Nxe2 Qxd7 14. Bd4 Bxd4 15. Qxd4 (15. Nxd4 Nc6) 15... Qc6 (15... Nc6 16. Qd5 Rae8 17. Nc3 Qe6! { Clear the way for f7-f5, but also trade queens. } 18. Rad1 f5! 19. exf5 Rxf5 20. Rde1 Rxd5 21. Rxe6 Re5! 22. Rxe8+ Rxe8 23. Rd1 Kf7 { King is going to defend d6 after c7-c6 is playedd } 24. Kf1 Ne5! 25. b3 Nd7 { Excellent maneuvering. The knight is about to go to f6 is guard f6. } 26. Nd5 c6! { Though weakening, black’s pieces are not tied down Black’s rook will not be stuck on c7 allowing Re1-e7 } (26... Rc8?! 27. Re1! { And the check on e7 is unavoidable unless Ne5-c6 get the knight back to the bad square. }) 27. Nf4 Re4! { Another little combination. Indirectly protect d6 pawn and put the king behind the rook. } 28. g3 Ke7 29. Ne2 Nc5 30. f3 Re3 31. Kf2 Rd3 32. Rxd3 Nxd3+ 33. Ke3 Nb4 { 1/2-1/2 }) *


