1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 d5 4. Nbd2 Be7 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Bd3 c5 7. c3 b6 8. O-O Bb7 9. Ne5 Nxe5 10. dxe5 Nd7 11. Bf4 (11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. f4) 11... Qc7 12. Nf3 h6! { Try to make use of the awkward bishop on f4 } 13. b4! g5 (13... cxb4 14. cxb4 Bxb4 15. Nd4) 14. Bg3 h5 15. h4 { Inducing g5-g4. Using pawn ram to stop black’s pawn from rolling forward. } 15... gxh4 16. Bf4 O-O-O 17. a4? { Now the queenside pawn ram will be neutralized. } (17. bxc5! bxc5 (17... Nxc5 18. Nd4 { With no Nxe5 anymore, the knight goes to d4 }) 18. Rb1) 17... c4 18. Be2 a6!! { A good evaluation is made by Petrosian:
The e5 pawn tied down white’s knight so it is hard to get to d4
Black can focus on the kingside attack because now all white’s attack on the queenside is blocked/ } 19. Kh1 Rdg8 20. Rg1 Rg4 21. Qd2 Rhg8 22. a5 b5 23. Rad1 Bf8 24. Nh2 Nxe5 { Now exchange sacrifice is made. } 25. Nxg4 hxg4 26. e4 Bd6 27. Qe3 Nd7 28. Bxd6 Qxd6 29. Rd4 e5 30. Rd2 f5! 31. exd5 (31. exf5 Nf6! { H3 gxh3 and d4 is happening }) 31... f4! 32. Qe4 Nf6 33. Qf5+ Kb8 34. f3 Bc8 35. Qb1 g3 36. Re1 h3 37. Bf1 Rh8 38. gxh3 Bxh3 39. Kg1 Bxf1 40. Kxf1 e4! 41. Qd1 (41. fxe4 f3) 41... Ng4! 42. fxg4 f3 43. Rg2 fxg2+ { 0-1 } *


